{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Recently, a new trend of tuning complex scattering media in situ with a large number of adjustable degrees of freedom (DOFs) emerges across scales and wave phenomena (see also Supplementary Note 1).",
    "Currently the most prominent example are metasurface-programmable smart radio environments, foreseen to play a pivotal role in next-generation wireless networks [1] [2] [3].",
    "The same concept also underlies promising implementations of reconfigurable holographic antennas [4] [5] [6] and wave-based signal processors 7, 8 in the microwave regime, and emerges in nanophotonics [9] [10] [11], optics [12] [13] [14] and room acoustics 15, 16, too.",
    "However, the inverse-design problem of identifying a configuration of the DOFs that yields a desired system transfer function is notoriously difficult for two reasons.",
    "First, the mapping from a configuration to its transfer function is a priori unknown in complex media for which detailed geometrical and/or material descriptions are usually not available."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
